  "analysis": "The statement is true. It is a known theorem (Ford, Green, Konyagin, Maynard, Tao, 2016) that for any C>0, there are infinitely many n such that p_{n+1} - p_n > C * (log n) * (log log n) * (log log log log n) / (log log log n)^2. This is a lower bound on maximal prime gaps.",
  "candidate_moves": [
    "Invoke the theorem of Ford-Green-Konyagin-Maynard-Tao (2016) on large gaps between primes.",
    "Note that the result is unconditional and proven using the method of constructing long intervals of composite numbers with prime factors from a carefully chosen set.",
    "Alternatively, one can reference the earlier result by Westzynthius (1931) that there are infinitely many gaps larger than C log n, but the given bound is stronger."
  ]
}
